\begin_layout Section
Weather-Coupled Irrigation Scheduling Benchmark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:WeatherProblem"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Background of the Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Background"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed benchmark is motivated by the need to represent irrigation scheduling as a genuinely coupled seasonal decision process rather than as a separable stage-wise water allocation rule.
 In realistic irrigation environments,
 the amount of water applied at one stage influences not only the immediate water balance of the crop,
 but also subsequent storage,
 drainage,
 evaporative losses,
 and the cumulative preservation of seasonal productivity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Allen,Doorenbos,Wang,Linker,Li,Zhao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This makes the domain naturally suitable for benchmark construction aimed at non-separable and state-dependent continuous optimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benchmark is intentionally synthetic in the sense that all exogenous profiles are generated analytically from the normalized stage coordinate,
 yet it remains literature-informed in its semantic structure.
 To make this grounding explicit,
 the following correspondences between benchmark components and agronomic concepts are noted.
 The stage-wise crop evapotranspiration demand 
\begin_inset Formula $ETc_{i}=ETo_{i}·Kc_{i}·Δt$
\end_inset

 follows the standard reference-evapotranspiration construction of the FAO Penman Monteith framework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Allen"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 in which a reference atmospheric demand 
\begin_inset Formula $ETo$
\end_inset

 is scaled by a crop-specific coefficient Kc to obtain actual crop water requirements.
 The multiplicative yield-preservation factor 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{rel}=∏y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is consistent with the classical yield-response-to-water model of Doorenbos and Kassam 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doorenbos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which relates relative yield reduction to relative evapotranspiration deficit through a crop-specific sensitivity coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $Ky$
\end_inset

.
 The recursive soil-water storage transition 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i+1}=f(S_{i},rain_{i},I_{i}^{eff},...)$
\end_inset

 reflects the widely adopted soil water-balance approach used in simulation-optimization frameworks for irrigation scheduling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Linker,Li-1,Zhao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 in which the storage state at each stage depends on incoming water,
 drainage,
 and evaporative losses from the preceding stage.
 The weather-dependent profiles for heat,
 wind,
 rainfall,
 and tariff represent stylized seasonal patterns that capture the qualitative behavior documented in weather-aware scheduling studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jamal,Wang"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 although their specific functional forms are chosen for analytical convenience rather than site-specific fidelity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond these literature-informed components,
 additional oscillatory,
 thresholded,
 and deceptive mechanisms are deliberately embedded to produce a challenging optimization landscape.
 These include the oscillatory modulation of irrigation efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $η_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

,
 which generates repeated local attraction basins,
 the threshold-triggered deep drainage loss,
 which introduces nonsmooth regime changes,
 and the deceptive preferred-window penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{win}$
\end_inset

,
 which attracts solvers toward irrigation levels that are suboptimal under the full objective.
 These mechanisms are synthetic ruggedness generators with no claim to precise field physics,
 they are introduced to make the benchmark genuinely difficult for modern continuous optimizers while remaining structurally interpretable.
 As a result,
 the problem should be interpreted as a literature-informed optimization benchmark with agronomic meaning,
 not as a calibrated digital twin of a particular field or crop system."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mathematical Formulation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Formulation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D\geq4$
\end_inset

 denote the problem dimension,
 and let
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{D})^{\mathsf{T}}$
\end_inset

 be the decision vector,
 where
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the irrigation depth (mm) applied at stage 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of a synthetic growing season.
 The feasible set is the hyper-rectangle
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega=[0,80]^{D},\qquad0\leq x_{i}\leq80,\qquad i=1,\ldots,D.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only hard constraints imposed on the problem are the box bounds 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq x_{i}\leq80$
\end_inset

 on the decision variables.
 The internal storage state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 is maintained within admissible bounds 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\,S_{i}^{max}]$
\end_inset

 through the clipping operator in the storage transition equation,
 which acts as an implicit state constraint enforced by construction rather than by external penalization.
 All remaining operational constraints are treated as soft penalties incorporated directly into the objective function:
 the seasonal water budget is softly constrained through 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{budget}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
,
 which penalizes deviation from the target 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{D}=28D$
\end_inset

,
 peak hydraulic demand is softly constrained through 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{peak}$
\end_inset

 and terminal storage is regularized through 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{term}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
.
 This soft-constraint formulation is deliberate,
 as it preserves the box-constrained structure of the search domain while embedding operational feasibility requirements into the landscape topology of the objective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The season length is fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $120$
\end_inset

 days,
 so the stage duration is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t=\frac{120}{D},
\]

\end_inset

 and the normalized stage coordinate is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{i}=\frac{i}{D+1},\qquad i=1,\ldots,D.
\]

\end_inset

 Recommended difficult dimensions are 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\{24,30,50,70,100\}$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=30$
\end_inset

 suitable for routine experiments and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=50$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

 producing substantially harder landscapes for population-based optimizers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make the benchmark fully deterministic and self-contained,
 all exogenous weather and crop coefficients are generated analytically from the normalized stage coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
.
 No stochastic,
 scenario-based,
 or externally sampled weather realizations are involved:
 every weather profile is a fixed,
 closed-form trigonometric function of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 that produces identical values for any given dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 This design choice eliminates all sources of exogenous randomness from the benchmark,
 ensuring that any variability in optimization outcomes is attributable solely to the stochastic search process of the optimizer and not to weather input uncertainty.
 The specific functional forms are chosen to reproduce qualitative seasonal patterns (e.g.,
 mid-season peaks in temperature and evapotranspiration,
 early-season dominance of rainfall) that are consistent with the general behavior documented in weather-aware scheduling studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jamal,Wang"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 although they do not represent any particular geographic location or climate record.
 The stage-wise profiles are defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ETo_{i}=2.8+3.2\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Kc_{i}=0.55+0.65\sin(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
rain_{i}=8+18\cos^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ky_{i}=0.85+0.55\sin(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
heat_{i}=0.40+0.60\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
wind_{i}=0.35+0.65\cos^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tariff_{i}=0.90+0.18\sin(2\pi s_{i}+0.20),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{base,i}=0.78+0.10\cos(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{i}=0.52+0.18\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i}^{max}=50+20\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
freq_{i}=0.22+0.09\sin(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{i}=0.70i+0.30\sin(2\pi s_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

 The crop evapotranspiration demand follows the standard evapotranspiration-based construction
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ETc_{i}=ETo_{i}Kc_{i}\Delta t,
\]

\end_inset

 which grounds the benchmark in classical irrigation science 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Naser"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $Ky_{i}$
\end_inset

 is used as a stage sensitivity factor in the relative yield-preservation component,
 consistent with the general idea of yield response to water stress 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doorenbos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first major source of difficulty is local decision coupling.
 A neighbor-coupled hydraulic load is introduced as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{i}=0.60x_{i}+0.25x_{i-1}+0.15x_{i+1},
\]

\end_inset

 with boundary conventions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=x_{D+1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Effective irrigation efficiency is then defined by the oscillatory nonlinear law
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=\eta_{base,i}\Big[1-0.22\sin^{2}(freq_{i}x_{i}+\phi_{i})-0.10\sin^{2}(0.07N_{i}+0.50\phi_{i})\Big],
\]

\end_inset

 clipped to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.45,1.00]$
\end_inset

,
 and the effective irrigation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{i}^{eff}=\eta_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})x_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 These oscillatory factors are synthetic ruggedness generators.
 They are not intended to claim precise field physics,
 they are introduced to generate repeated attraction basins and to make coordinate-wise search substantially less effective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second major source of difficulty is path dependence through a synthetic soil-water storage state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The initial storage is fixed by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{1}=0.35S_{1}^{max}.
\]

\end_inset

 The total water available at stage
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{i}=rain_{i}+I_{i}^{eff}+0.55S_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the stage deficit and surplus are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
deficit_{i}=\max(0,ETc_{i}-A_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
surplus_{i}=\max(0,A_{i}-ETc_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

 Deep drainage is modeled by the thresholded term
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
deep_{i}=\max(0,surplus_{i}-0.35S_{i}^{max})\Big[0.55+0.20wind_{i}+0.15\sin^{2}(0.11x_{i}+\phi_{i})\Big],
\]

\end_inset

 recharge is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
recharge_{i}=\rho_{i}\max(0,surplus_{i}-deep_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

 evaporative loss is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
evaploss_{i}=(0.08+0.10heat_{i}+0.04wind_{i})S_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the storage transition is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i+1}=\mathrm{clip}\Big(0.82S_{i}+recharge_{i}-evaploss_{i},\,0,\,S_{i}^{max}\Big).
\]

\end_inset

 This recursion makes the objective stateful:
 changing one variable can alter the effective optimization landscape seen by many subsequent variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The storage transition is nonlinear due to the 
\begin_inset Formula $max(·)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $clip(·)$
\end_inset

 operators appearing in the drainage,
 surplus,
 deficit,
 and recharge terms.
 Rainfall and effective irrigation enter additively in the total available water 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}=\text{rain}_{i}+I_{i}^{eff}+0.55\,S_{i}$
\end_inset

 while evapotranspiration demand 
\begin_inset Formula $ETc_{i}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 is subtracted through the deficit-surplus split.
 The clipping to 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,S_{i}^{max}]$
\end_inset

 ensures that the storage state remains non-negative and bounded at every stage,
 guaranteeing feasibility of the dynamic system.
 The contraction factor 0.82 in the transition ensures that the autonomous dynamics (without recharge) are inherently stable,
 preventing unbounded state accumulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A multiplicative relative yield-preservation term is included to prevent the problem from collapsing into a pure cost minimization model.
 The relative water-satisfaction ratio is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{i}=\min\Big(1,\frac{A_{i}}{ETc_{i}+\varepsilon}\Big),\qquad\varepsilon=10^{-12},
\]

\end_inset

 the stage stress is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
stress_{i}=1-r_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the stage contribution to yield preservation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=\mathrm{clip}\Big(1-Ky_{i}stress_{i}^{1.35}-0.08heat_{i}\exp\Big(-\frac{A_{i}}{0.35ETc_{i}+1}\Big),\,0.02,\,1\Big).
\]

\end_inset

 The season-level relative yield factor is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{rel}=\prod_{i=1}^{D}y_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 The multiplicative construction is deliberate:
 a few severely stressed stages can dominate many small local improvements,
 which makes the global tradeoff structure significantly more deceptive than in additive reward formulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doorenbos,Linker,Li,Zhao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benchmark is posed as the minimization problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{\boldsymbol{x}\in[0,80]^{D}}f(\boldsymbol{x}),
\]

\end_inset

 where
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\boldsymbol{x})=C_{water}+C_{pump}+P_{def}+P_{exc}+P_{smooth}+P_{res}+P_{int}+P_{win}+P_{term}+P_{budget}+P_{peak}-350Y_{rel}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To clarify the role and origin of each term,
 the eleven components of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 are organized into three categories according to their design rationale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first category contains terms that are directly motivated by agronomic and operational practice.
 The water-cost term 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{water}$
\end_inset

 represents the direct economic cost of water application,
 which is a primary objective in any irrigation scheduling formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jamal,Wang"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The pumping-cost term 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{pump}$
\end_inset

 captures the energy cost associated with pressurized water delivery,
 a well-recognized component of irrigation operating expenses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The deficit penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{def}$
\end_inset

 penalizes unmet crop water demand,
 reflecting the agronomic principle that water stress reduces yield 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doorenbos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The excess penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{exc}$
\end_inset

 penalizes over-irrigation that leads to deep drainage and waterlogging,
 consistent with the water-balance perspective in which surplus water beyond the root zone is a resource loss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Allen,Linker"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The terminal storage penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{term}$
\end_inset

 encourages the preservation of soil moisture at the end of the season,
 a common objective in multi-season water management 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Li-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The seasonal budget penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{budget}$
\end_inset

 softly constrains total water use over the growing season,
 reflecting practical water-rights or allocation limits [14].
 The multiplicative yield factor 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{rel}$
\end_inset

 aggregates stage-wise crop productivity into a seasonal yield metric,
 following the classical yield-response-to-water framework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doorenbos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second category contains terms that model realistic operational concerns but whose specific functional forms are stylized.
 The smoothness penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{smooth}$
\end_inset

 discourages abrupt changes in irrigation between consecutive stages,
 reflecting practical constraints on irrigation system ramping and scheduling regularity.
 The peak-load penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{peak}$
\end_inset

 penalizes excessive instantaneous hydraulic demand,
 which in practice can exceed the capacity of pumping and conveyance infrastructure.
 The neighbor-interaction penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{int}$
\end_inset

 captures the operational coupling between adjacent irrigation stages,
 in which the cumulative load from consecutive high-application periods can create delivery bottlenecks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third category contains terms that are deliberately synthetic and are introduced to generate specific landscape difficulty features for benchmarking purposes.
 The resonance penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{res}$
\end_inset

 and the deceptive preferred-window penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{win}$
\end_inset

 are oscillatory and phase-shifted ruggedness generators designed to create dense local attractors and misleading basins that make the optimization landscape genuinely challenging for modern solvers.
 These terms have no direct agronomic counterpart,
 their role is purely to increase the benchmark's difficulty in a controlled and ablatable manner,
 as verified experimentally in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ExpResults"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The water-cost term is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{water}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}tariff_{i}x_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the pumping-cost term is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{pump}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}0.0045N_{i}^{2}\Big[1+0.35\sin^{2}(0.08x_{i}+0.60\phi_{i})\Big].
\]

\end_inset

 A weather-modulated shock factor is introduced by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
shock_{i}=1+0.18heat_{i}\sin^{2}(0.09x_{i}+1.3wind_{i}+\phi_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

 and the deficit and excess penalties are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{def}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}(0.12+0.06heat_{i})deficit_{i}^{2}shock_{i},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{exc}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}(0.05+0.05wind_{i})\Big(deep_{i}^{2}+0.30surplus_{i}^{2}\Big).
\]

\end_inset

 Temporal roughness and local resonance are imposed by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{smooth}=\sum_{i=2}^{D}(0.06+0.02wind_{i})(x_{i}-x_{i-1})^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{res}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}8.0(1+0.70heat_{i})\sin^{2}(freq_{i}x_{i}+\phi_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

 Neighbor-stage overloading and bilinear coupling are represented by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{int}=\sum_{i=2}^{D}\Big[0.018\max(0,x_{i}+0.55x_{i-1}-58)^{2}+0.025x_{i}x_{i-1}\Big].
\]

\end_inset

 A deceptive preferred-window term is defined through
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i}=18+26\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{win}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}\Big(0.014+0.010\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i})\Big)(x_{i}-\mu_{i})^{2}\Big[1+0.40\sin^{2}(0.06x_{i}+\phi_{i})\Big].
\]

\end_inset

 The terminal storage penalty is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{term}=1.2\Big(S_{D+1}-0.45S_{D}^{max}\Big)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

 the soft seasonal budget penalty uses
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{D}=28D,
\]

\end_inset

 and is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{budget}=0.010\Big(\sum_{i=1}^{D}x_{i}-B_{D}\Big)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

 while the peak-load penalty is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{peak}=0.035\sum_{i=1}^{D}\max(0,N_{i}-62)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

 The complete problem is therefore a box-constrained,
 deterministic,
 strongly non-separable,
 rugged,
 and partially nonsmooth minimization benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No closed-form global optimum is assumed known.
 This is intentional and is part of the benchmark design.
 The objective contains repeated oscillatory structures,
 threshold-triggered regime changes,
 clipped internal states,
 recursive storage dynamics,
 multiplicative stage aggregation,
 and coupled penalties.
 Consequently,
 the landscape contains many local minima and deceptive tradeoffs,
 and performance cannot be inferred from low-dimensional intuition alone.
 From the perspective of benchmark design,
 the difficulty comes from the simultaneous presence of six mechanisms:
 recursive state propagation,
 local oscillatory efficiency modulation,
 thresholded drainage and peak penalties,
 multiplicative yield aggregation,
 neighbor coupling through 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 and soft preferred-window structure that competes with the remaining terms instead of revealing the optimum.
 For these reasons,
 the benchmark is substantially harder than a smooth irrigation cost-yield tradeoff model while remaining interpretable as a weather-coupled irrigation scheduling problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although no closed-form global optimum is available for the full benchmark formulation,
 the fully simplified variant 
\begin_inset Formula $ALL_{OFF}$
\end_inset

 provides a tractable reference point for absolute performance calibration.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $ALL_{OFF}$
\end_inset

 formulation,
 all embedded difficulty mechanisms are disabled and the resulting landscape is smooth and convex-like:
 as demonstrated in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ExpResults"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the methods arq,
 cmaes,
 lmcmaes,
 lracmaes,
 jso,
 and mlshaderl converge to identical objective values with 100% success rates and zero standard deviation across all dimensions,
 establishing a consensus empirical optimum that can serve as a lower bound reference for the full formulation.
 The optimality gap for any method on the full benchmark can therefore be estimated as the difference between its achieved objective value and the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $ALL_{OFF}$
\end_inset

 consensus value,
 providing an absolute rather than purely relative measure of solution quality.
 This approach is consistent with established practice in black-box benchmarking:
 the BBOB platform and the CEC suites both rely on inter-algorithm relative comparison as the primary performance metric when closed-form optima are not analytically available,
 and the availability of a tractable simplified variant with a verifiable consensus optimum provides an additional calibration layer that is rarely present in classical synthetic benchmarks.
\end_layout

