\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:times"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports the mean wall-clock time per run for each method across all five dimensions.
 The benchmark's objective function is inexpensive to evaluate:
 for eight of the ten methods,
 the time per run ranges from 0.22 seconds at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24$
\end_inset

 to approximately 1.6 seconds at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

 on the reference hardware.
 The exceptions are cmaes and lracmaes,
 both of which exhibit substantially higher wall-clock times that grow with dimension:
 cmaes from 2.53 seconds at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24$
\end_inset

 to 380.21 seconds at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

,
 and lracmaes from 4.87 seconds at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24$
\end_inset

 to 800.07 seconds at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

,
 reflecting the 
\begin_inset Formula $O(D²)$
\end_inset

 cost of their covariance matrix adaptation mechanisms rather than the benchmark's evaluation cost.
 A complete 30-run experimental campaign at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

 therefore requires less than one minute for most methods,
 confirming that the benchmark is computationally lightweight and suitable for routine algorithm development,
 with the caveat that covariance-based methods incur substantially higher per-run costs at large dimensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The recommended upper dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

 is intentional and sufficient for the purposes of this benchmark.
 As demonstrated in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ExpResults"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 all ten competing methods achieve success rates of 
\begin_inset Formula $3\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

,
 representing the minimum observable rate under the 30-run protocol.
 This universal solver failure indicates that the benchmark has already reached a difficulty ceiling at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

:
 extending to 
\begin_inset Formula $D=200$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D=500$
\end_inset

 would not produce qualitatively new algorithmic findings but would instead amplify the computational cost of the covariance-based methods (notably cmaes,
 whose wall-clock time scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(D^{2})$
\end_inset

,
 reaching 380 seconds per run at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

) to levels that preclude routine experimental use.
 Furthermore,
 the combinatorial growth argument presented in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Discussion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 establishes that the effective number of local attractors scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $5^{D}$
\end_inset

,
 yielding approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $5^{100}\approx10^{69}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

,
 a landscape complexity that is already far beyond the exhaustive coverage capacity of any population-based solver.
 The benchmark is therefore not limited by its upper dimension but by the fundamental intractability of its landscape structure,
 which manifests fully within the recommended range 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\{24,30,50,70,100\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parameter sensitivity analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:sensitivity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess how sensitive the benchmark's optimization landscape is to its internal coefficients,
 a one-at-a-time perturbation study was conducted on six parameters that directly control the primary difficulty mechanisms of the benchmark.
 These parameters were selected because the ablation study in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ExpResults"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 identified the oscillatory efficiency and multiplicative yield mechanisms as the two most consequential sources of landscape difficulty,
 and the six parameters studied here are the numerical coefficients that directly modulate these mechanisms.
 These parameters are:
 the oscillatory efficiency amplitude (default 0.22),
 which governs the depth of the sinusoidal modulation in 
\begin_inset Formula $η_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

,
 the resonance penalty weight (default 8.0),
 which scales the local ruggedness term 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{res}$
\end_inset

,
 the oscillation frequency base and amplitude (defaults 0.22 and 0.09),
 which jointly determine the density of local attractors through 
\begin_inset Formula $freq_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 and the yield-sensitivity base and amplitude (defaults 0.85 and 0.55),
 which control the stage-wise crop stress coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $Ky_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Each parameter was varied independently across its tested range while all others were held at their default values.
 For each setting,
 30 independent runs of mlshaderl were executed at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=30$
\end_inset

,
 and the mean best objective value,
 standard deviation,
 minimum,
 and maximum were recorded.
 The main effect of each parameter is defined as the difference between the highest and lowest mean best values observed across its tested range.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:sensitivity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports the complete results,
 and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sensitivity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 visualizes the sensitivity profiles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The one-at-a-time perturbation protocol adopted in this study is a deliberate and well-established choice for benchmarks whose primary goal is mechanism transparency rather than global parameter optimization.
 Single-factor variation isolates the individual contribution of each coefficient to the observed landscape difficulty,
 a property that would be obscured by factorial or Latin hypercube designs in which multiple parameters vary simultaneously.
 This interpretability is essential for benchmark users who wish to adjust a specific difficulty mechanism without inadvertently altering others.
 The analysis was conducted at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=30$
\end_inset

 because this dimension lies at the transition between partial and universal solver failure in the full formulation,
 making it the most sensitive and informative setting for detecting landscape changes induced by parameter perturbations.
 The use of mlshaderl as the reference solver is justified by its consistent position among the top-performing methods across all dimensions and variants in Section 2.4,
 its low run-to-run variability (SD below 15 units at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=30$
\end_inset

),
 and its archive-based mechanism,
 which provides stable convergence behavior that makes mean best objective values a reliable proxy for landscape difficulty rather than a reflection of solver-specific search artifacts.
\end_layout

