\begin_layout Subsection
Comparative Difficulty Assessment on Classical Benchmarks
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:otherProblems"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To position the difficulty of the proposed benchmark relative to established test functions,
 the nine optimizers that are common to both experiments arq,
 clpso,
 cmaes,
 ga,
 jso,
 lmcmaes,
 lracmaes,
 mlshaderl,
 and acor were evaluated on four classical continuous optimization benchmarks at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=30$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=50$
\end_inset

 under the same experimental protocol (30 independent runs,
 identical evaluation budget).
 The four benchmark functions were selected to represent distinct difficulty profiles that are individually present in the proposed irrigation benchmark but rarely combined in a single classical test function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ackley function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ackley"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a widely used multimodal benchmark with a nearly separable structure and an exponentially decaying envelope that creates a broad basin surrounding the global optimum.
 It was selected because its multimodal character provides a baseline for assessing how the solvers handle oscillatory local structure in the absence of inter-variable coupling.
 The Rastrigin function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rastrigin"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a strongly multimodal,
 separable function whose cosine-based oscillatory landscape produces a dense lattice of local minima a structure that is directly analogous to the oscillatory efficiency modulation 
\begin_inset Formula $η_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 embedded in the proposed benchmark.
 Its inclusion allows a controlled comparison between separable and non-separable oscillatory difficulty.
 The Rosenbrock function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rosenbrock"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a unimodal but non-separable function characterized by a narrow curved valley,
 making it a standard test for the ability of optimizers to follow non-separable gradient structure.
 It was selected to isolate the contribution of non-separability to search difficulty,
 independent of multimodality.
 The Schwefel function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schwefel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 features a deceptive global structure in which the second-best local minimum is geometrically distant from the global optimum,
 creating a landscape that misleads solvers toward suboptimal regions.
 This deceptive character is analogous to the preferred-window penalty 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{win}$
\end_inset

 and the multiplicative yield aggregation 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{rel}$
\end_inset

 in the proposed benchmark.
 Table 
